window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2023>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2023","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"You are provided with a metre rule, two loads, P and Q, a knife edge, K, a set of masses, m and a piece of string.     Use the diagram above as a guide to perform the experiment.    (i) With no loads hanging on the metre rule, balance the metre rule horizontally on the knife edge. Record the position, G, of the knife edge on the balanced metre rule.    (ii) Suspend P securely at 15 cm from G, and Q securely at 10 cm from G. The positions of G, P and Q should not be altered throughout the experiment.    (iii) Using a mass, m = 40, balance the metre rule horizontally. Measure and record the distance, y, of m from G.    (iv) Evaluate m-1.    (v) Repeat the procedure for m = 50 g, 60 g, 70 g and 80 g. In each case, record the distance, y, and evaluate m-1.     (vi) Tabulate the results.    (vii) Plot a graph with m-1 as ordinate and y as abscissa.    (viii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (ix) Determine the value of mP given that 15mP = s-1 + 200    (x) From the graph, deduce the mass, m, that would produce a balance distance, y = 27.5 cm.    (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure good results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"G = 50.0 cm    S/Nm(g)y(cm)m-1(g-1)14030.40.02525024.40.02036020.40.01747017.50.01458013.40.013        (viii) s = \u25b3m\u22121\u25b3y\\frac{\u25b3m^{-1}}{\u25b3y}\u25b3y\u25b3m\u22121\u200b = m2\u22121\u2212m1\u22121y2\u2212y1\\frac{m^{-1}_{2}-m^{-1}_{1}}{y_{2}-y_{1}}y2\u200b\u2212y1\u200bm2\u22121\u200b\u2212m1\u22121\u200b\u200b = 0.024\u22120.01429\u221216\\frac{0.024-0.014}{29-16}29\u2212160.024\u22120.014\u200b = 0.0113\\frac{0.01}{13}130.01\u200b = 7.69 \u00d7 10-4 g-1cm-1    (ix) 15mP = s-1 + 200    15mP = 17.69\u00d710\u22124\\frac{1}{7.69\u00d710^{-4}}7.69\u00d710\u221241\u200b + 200    15mP = 1300.39 + 200    15mP = 1500.39    mP = 100.0 gcm    (x) When y = 27.5 cm, m-1 = 0.021 g-1. \u2234 m = 10.021\\frac{1}{0.021}0.0211\u200b = 47.62 g    (xi) Precautions:    1. I ensured the metre rule was balanced horizontally on the knife edge before taking any readings to eliminate systematic errors.    2. I avoided parallax errors by positioning my eye directly perpendicular to the scale when reading the metre rule.    3. I verified that the positions of G, P, and Q were not altered throughout the experiment to maintain consistency.    4. I ensured that the string and suspended masses were securely fastened to prevent unintended movement.    5. I placed the knife edge on a stable, flat surface to avoid disturbances during measurements.    6. I ensured that environmental factors like vibrations or air currents did not affect the setup.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2023>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2023","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"State the two conditions necessary for a body to be in equilibrium","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The two conditions necessary for a body to be in equilibrium are:    1.\tThe First Condition of Equilibrium (Translational Equilibrium):  The vector sum of all forces acting on the body must be zero (or the sum of upward forces = the sum of downward forces). Mathematically,  \u2211F = 0  This ensures that the body does not accelerate linearly and remains at rest or in uniform motion.    2.\tThe Second Condition of Equilibrium (Rotational Equilibrium):  The sum of all torques about any axis must be zero (or the sum of clockwise moments = the sum of anticlockwise moments). Mathematically,  \u2211\u03c4 = 0  This ensures the body does not rotate or rotates with constant angular velocity.    These conditions together maintain the stability of the body in both translational and rotational motion.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2023>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2023","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"Two forces 4 N and 3 N act at right angles to each other, calculate the equilibrant of the system of forces.    (Provide your answer with the unit e.g 123 m)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"R2 = 42 + 32    R2 = 16 + 9    R2 = 25    R = &radic;25&nbsp; = 5 N    \u2234 The equilibrant is a force of 5 N that acts in the direction opposite to that of the resultant force, R, effectively balancing out the resultant and bringing the system into equilibrium.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2023>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2023","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"You are provided with a rectangular block, a drawing board, drawing sheets, four optical pins and other necessary materials.  Use the diagram above as a guide to perform the experiment.    (i) Measure and record the width of the block.    (ii) Draw the outline ABCD of the block on a drawing sheet. Mark a point, Q on AB such that AQ = 1.5 cm. Draw the normal RQT as shown in the diagram above.    (iii) Draw a line UQ making an angle i = 10\u00b0 with the normal RQT.    (iv) Insert pins P1 and P2 on the UQ. Look through the side DC of the block and insert two other pins, P3 and P4 which appear to be in a straight line with the images of P1 and P2.    (v) Remove the block and mark the positions of P3 and P4. Draw a straight line joining P3 and P4 and extend it to meet DC at E.    (vi) Produce a line UQ to meet DC at point F. Draw a straight line EQ.    (vii) Measure and record the angle, r, length, EF = d, and evaluate tan i, tan r and V = (tan i - tan r).    (viii) Using different outlines of the block, repeat the procedure for i = 20\u00b0, 30\u00b0, 40\u00b0 and 50\u00b0. In each case, measure and record r, d and evaluate tan i, tan r and V.    (ix) Tabulate the results.    (x) Plot a graph with d on the vertical axis and V on the horizontal axis.    (xi) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (xii) State two precautions taken to ensure good results.    [attach the traces to this booklet]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Width of the block = 5.2 cm    S/Ni\u00b0r\u00b0tan itan rVd(cm)11050.1760.0870.0890.422090.3640.1580.2060.7330190.5770.3440.2331.1440250.8390.4660.3731.4550271.1920.5100.6824.0            (xi) s = \u25b3d\u25b3V\\frac{\u25b3d}{\u25b3V}\u25b3V\u25b3d\u200b = d2\u2212d1V2\u2212V1\\frac{d_{2}-d_{1}}{V_{2}-V_{1}}V2\u200b\u2212V1\u200bd2\u200b\u2212d1\u200b\u200b = 2.6\u22120.50.5\u22120.15\\frac{2.6-0.5}{0.5-0.15}0.5\u22120.152.6\u22120.5\u200b = 2.10.35\\frac{2.1}{0.35}0.352.1\u200b = 6 cm    (xii) Precautions:    1. I ensured the rectangular glass block was cleaned properly to prevent any distortions of the light rays.    2. I avoided parallax errors when locating the image in the rectangular glass block by ensuring my line of sight was directly in line with the measurement points.    3. I ensured the protractor was aligned correctly and avoided parallax error when reading angles to guarantee accurate angular measurements.    4. I erected the pins securely, ensuring they were upright and spaced evenly for precise visual alignment.    5. I maintained even spacing between the pins to ensure uniform measurement of the light path.    6. I kept the setup stable, ensuring there was no movement that could alter the readings.    7. I clearly marked the measurement points on the setup to improve accuracy when reading angles and distances.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2023>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2023","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State the condition for the occurrence of total internal reflection at air-glass interface.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"For total internal reflection to occur at the air-glass interface, the following two conditions must be met:  1.\tThe light must travel from a denser medium (glass) to a rarer medium (air).  2.\tThe angle of incidence must be greater than the critical angle.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2023>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2023","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State Snell's law.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Snell's law states that the ratio of the sine of the angle of incidence to the sine of the angle of refraction is constant for a given pair of media.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2023>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2023","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"You are provided with a rheostat, an ammeter, a voltmeter, 1 \u03a9 standard resistor, a key, a source of electricity of emf, E and connecting wires.     (i) Use the electrical components provided to connect the circuit as shown in the diagram leaving the circuit open.    (ii) Connect the voltmeter to the terminals of the battery and record the voltmeter reading Vo.    (iii) Close the key and adjust the rheostat so that the ammeter reads, I = 0.3 A.  Record the corresponding voltmeter reading, V.    (iv) Evaluate I-1 and G = VI\\frac{V}{I}IV\u200b    (v) Repeat the experiment for four other values of I = 0.5 A, 0.7 A, 0.9 A and 1.1 A. In each case, record the corresponding value of V, and evaluate and G.    (vi) Tabulate the results.    (vii) Plot a graph with I-1 on the vertical axis and G on the horizontal axis.    (viii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (ix) Using the graph, determine the value of V for G = 2.5.    (x) State two precautions taken to ensure good results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Vo = 3.00 V    S/NI(A)V(V)I-1(A-1)G(V/A)10.31.703.335.67020.51.502.003.00030.71.301.431.86040.91.101.111.22251.10.900.910.818        (viii) s = \u25b3I\u22121\u25b3G\\frac{\u25b3I^{-1}}{\u25b3G}\u25b3G\u25b3I\u22121\u200b = I2\u22121\u2212I1\u22121G2\u2212G1\\frac{I^{-1}_{2}-I^{-1}_{1}}{G_{2}-G_{1}}G2\u200b\u2212G1\u200bI2\u22121\u200b\u2212I1\u22121\u200b\u200b = 2.5\u221214\u22121\\frac{2.5-1}{4-1}4\u221212.5\u22121\u200b = 1.53\\frac{1.5}{3}31.5\u200b = 0.5 V-1    (ix) When G = 2.5 V/A, I-1 = 1.75 A-1.    Since G = VI\\frac{V}{I}IV\u200b = V \u00d7 I-1    2.5 = V \u00d7 1.75    V = 2.51.75\\frac{2.5}{1.75}1.752.5\u200b = 1.43 V    (x) Precautions:    1. I ensured there was no parallax error when reading the voltmeter and ammeter, making sure the readings were taken at eye level to avoid distortion.    2. I made sure all connections were properly tightened to avoid any loose connections that could cause inconsistent measurements or fluctuations in the circuit.    3. I verified that the rheostat was adjusted carefully to maintain the desired current without any abrupt changes.    4. I ensured the circuit was properly set up according to the provided diagram before closing the key to avoid any errors in the setup.    5. I performed multiple trials to minimize random errors and improve the reliability of the data.    6. I ensured the voltage and current measurements were recorded promptly to avoid any fluctuations or changes during the experiment.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2023>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2023","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"A battery of emf 4.5 V has a voltmeter connected to its terminals. If the combination is connected in series with a standard resistor and a key, it is observed that the voltmeter reading is less than 4.5 V when the key is closed. Explain the observation","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The voltmeter reading is less than the battery's emf (4.5 V) when the key is closed due to the voltage drop across both the internal resistance of the battery and the external standard resistor. As current flows through the circuit, the battery's internal resistance causes a reduction in the terminal voltage, and the voltage drop across the standard resistor further lowers the reading, making it less than the emf of the battery.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2023>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2023","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC ENERGY AND POWER","question":"An electric device draws 0.50 A in a 120 V circuit. Calculate the cost of using the device for 24 hours if the rate is $ 0.25 per KWh    (Provide your answer to 2 d.p and without the dollar sign)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"E = IVt = 0.50 \u00d7 120 \u00d7 24 = 1140 Wh = 1.44 kWh    Cost = 1.44 kWh \u00d7 $ 0.25 per KWh = $ 0.36","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];